'''Framework laws''' are [[law]]s that are more specific than [[constitution]]al provisions. They lay down general obligations and principles but leave to governing authorities the task of [[enactment of a bill|enacting]] the further [[legislation]] and other specific measures, as may be required.<ref>{{Citation |last = Knuth |first = Lidija |others = Margret Vidar |title = Constitutional and Legal Protection of the Right to Food around the World |year = 2011 |publisher = Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations |location = Rome |url = http://www.fao.org/righttofood/publi11/constitutional_2011.pdf |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/69IfZvFdH?url=http://www.fao.org/righttofood/publi11/constitutional_2011.pdf |archivedate = 20 July 2012 |deadurl = yes |df = }}.</ref>
